Forecasting Parking Demand - Numbers of Vacant Spots in Seattle

Yixuan Hu and Yuchen Zhang

December 21, 2018

1 Introduction

Searching for parking becomes a challenging task in the city around the world1. Discussing vacant spots is one way to reflect the parking demands. Parking demands highly relate to the social behaviors of citizens who commute back and forth within the city. Moreover, parking demands have high spatial dynamics and temporal dynamics. That is, parking demands vary at different time or date, and in different locations2. Even the drivers are familiar with the surrounding environment, it is still difficult for them to find a vacant spot since they lack the dynamic information within an exact space and time. The activity of cruising for curbside parking contributes to traffic congestion. The purpose of this project is to build a model to predict the parking demands in terms of numbers of vacant spots on a blockface scale.

Both drivers and traffic operators will have great interest in the prediction model: for drivers, the model can offer them the information on the numbers of vacant spots in specific locations and time that can potentially help drivers find available parking spots more efficiently in a timely manner; helping drivers is also helping the city, because we can mitigate the traffic congestion if the “cruising” behavior is alleviated.

However, an accurate prediction is difficult to achieve since there are so many factors that may influence the numbers of vacant spots. For example, the traffic flow in that specific time and location, the road characteristics in that space and the walkable distance to the final destination will all affect the drivers’ decisions. Spatial variables such as distance to schools, distance to tourist attractions and distance to Centric Business District will also have impacts on the numbers of vacant spots. Feature engineering can not only help us figure out the dominant factors but also the degree of impact.

Our overall modeling strategy is to introduce 16 predictors (independent variables) within our model to determine the numbers of vacant spots in the city of Seattle using Poisson Distribution. Due to the limiting computing power of our laptops and the quality of the dataset, we have to narrow our predictors from 45 to 16. After associated with the numbers of vacant spots, factors will be judged by their correlation and MAE (Mean Absolute Error). 25% test sample prediction and cross-validation (including spatial and temporal one) will also help to ensure the generalizability and accuracy of the predictive model.

In the test set, the mean absolute error (MAE) is 1.82.

2 Data

Data are mainly extracted from the City of Seattle Open Data portal. General Parking Information data such as Parking Space, Total_Vehicle_Count, Peak Hour and Road Types in large scales are from Annual Parking Study Dataset; Count_Flow Data are from 2016 Traffic Flow Counts Dataset; Street classifications and conditions in small scales are from Seattle Streets Dataset. Geographic locations for different locations are either shapefiles from Open Data Portal, such as public transit dataset and schools dataset, or geographic-coordinate from Google map. All the spatial data are projected by NAD 1983 StatePlane Washington North FIPS 4901 in Meters.

2.1 Model Description

In our prediction model, the dependent variable that represents the parking demands is the numbers of vacant spots. It is the function of the built environment that contains spatial and temporal factors, and the road characteristics. Our independent variables will totally have 16 predictors and fall into four categories, which are spatial predictors, temporal predictors, road characteristic predictors, and social predictors.

For the dependent variable, the number of vacant spots will be calculated from parking space and total vehicle counts. There are some negative numbers after subtracting the parking_space by total_vehicle_counts, because some areas will be over-parked. We replace all negative numbers by 0. The entire model will be predicted by Poisson regression because the model contains too many 0 that is not reasonable to use the linear regression model.

3 Method

The research methods can be generally separated into three parts: data wrangling, building the predictive model and testing the model.

3.1 Data Wrangling

We introduce potential factors that will influence the real situations in the specific time and location, which might affect drivers’ parking behaviors. For example, locations of schools, tourist attractions, and office buildings will influence peak hours, traffic flows in the morning and middays. The density of these specific infrastructures will also affect the parking demands in that surrounding area and ultimately influence the vacant spots. Therefore, Average Distance to nearest numbers of public infrastructures is an important variable.

Right now, the scale of our model is blockface. In order to calculate the distance, using K-Nearest Neighbor method, we need to transform the line data (blockface) into point data first. Therefore, we use mid-point of each blockface to represent that blockface. In the end, we will assign those point data back to the related blockface again. Besides numerical variables, we also include many categorical variables, such as road characteristics such as street classification and slope.

The temporal predictor is another important type in our model. Basically, all temporal data will be separated into three periods: morning (8am-11am); midday (11am-5/6pm); and evening (5pm-8/10pm). Because we find that daily parking fees are different in the same place by three different periods as we mentioned above.

3.2 Building a Predictive Model

We select the data that tend to associate with independent variables but not correlated with each other. For categorical data, we change them to be dummy variables. Then we use Poisson regression to build the predictive model.

3.3 Testing the Model

We basically test the predictive model in two ways: in-sample prediction and 25% test-sample prediction. In the in-sample prediction, we test the entire dataset and judge the accuracy of the result by the standardized coefficient and mean absolute error (MAE). In the 25% test-sample prediction, we test the model by k-fold cross-validation to ensure the generalizability of the model. Since temporal and spatial variables are vitally important in our model, we will also test the spatial cross-validation and temporal cross-validation to check the generalizability. Moran’s I is also calculated to check the spatial auto-correlation of the model.

4 Result

4.1 In-sample Model

4.1.1 Standardized Coefficient

Figure above represents the standardized coefficients for all numerical variables and some categorical variables. We can see that the most important variable here is the population density in 2016. This means that the spatial location of people has a strong influence on the model.

The figure above only includes the spatial and temporal numeric variables. We can see that peak hour (Y/N) has a relatively most strong influence on a model as a temporal variable. Meanwhile, median numbers of nearest several vacant spots also has strong relation with dependent variable as a spatial variable. Distance to nearest schools and garage also effectively affect the model as spatial variables.
For peak hour, the peak hour for each street is different. The coefficient demonstrates that peak hour is more important in the model that time itself.

4.2 Measure of Accuracy - MAE

Figure below is the map of Mean Absolute Error Across Space. The predicting power is stronger in downtown area rather than peripheral area.

We ran Moran’s I test to examine whether there is spatial autocorrelation in the error in different parking blockface. The Moran’s I is -0.0417 and the p-value of Moran I is 0.993, which is over 0.05. The Moran I is calculated close to zero. This means that there is no spatial autocorrelation. That is to say that, the model should be generalizable and doesn’t have systematic bias across space.
However, the Moran’s I test result is different as the MAE’s. One reason is that when calculating Moran’s I, most of time, it is calculating the downtown area. Therefore, the result of Maron I is different from what we visually see in the MAE map.

4.3 Out-of-sample Model and Cross-validation

4.3.1 25% Training Set

25% test-sample prediction should be more trustworthy than the in-sample prediction. From the above analysis, we have already known that in-sample prediction model is relatively sensitive to outliers and data mining. In general, 25% test-sample prediction model may better reflect the available information.

The goal for our predictive model is to be generalizable. In other word, the model should be distributed spatially. The data was separated into two parts-25% randomly selected test set and 75% training set for remaining data. By doing so, we can judge the performance of the model.

Here is the polished result for the 25% test-sample set. The Mean Absolute Error (MAE) of the test set is around 2.11. The result shows that the accuracy is moderate, and the generalizability is not that good

The mean absolute error of 25% training set is 2.12. The 25% training model is less accurate than the in-sample model.

4.3.2 K-fold Cross-validation

We use the cross-validation to test the generalizability of our model. The algorithm, we use in the test, is called “k-fold cross-validation (k-100)”. In other words, the original dataset is randomly partitioned by 100 equal sizes of subsamples. Then we can tell the effectiveness of the model. The place where the model may not be generalizable was where our model needs to improve.

Here is the result for the cross-validation (K=100), The Mean Absolute Error is around 1.9. The accuracy is moderate. That is, for instance, if that space has 10 actual vacant spots, the model will give the result with either 8 or 12 spots.

4.4 Generalizability Across Time and Space

4.4.1 Spatial Cross-validation

In order to do the spatial cross-validation, we separate our study area into three neighborhood area: downtown area, peripheral area at University District, and residential area at Capitol Hill.

MAE in Different Neighborhoods
Neighborhood MAE
CBD (Downtown) 1.733867
University District (Peripheral) 2.922975
Capitol Hill (Residential) 1.953299

We can see that the university district, which at the peripheral of Settle, obtains the largest mean absolute error (2.92). In center business district, which at downtown of Seattle, performs the best with the smallest mean absolute error (1.73). The residential area performs quite close to the original 25% test-sample model. The possible reason that causes this result might be due to the lack of data at the peripheral area. Most data are in the downtown. Therefore, this result also incrementally prove that this model is not generalizable enough to apply to all neighborhoods.

4.4.2 Temporal Cross-validation

Temporal cross-validation can help us to test the generalizability of the temporal variables.

First, we hold out Thursday’s data in the dotw (day of week). Then we use Tuesday and Wednesday’s data to to predict Thursday’s vacant spots. In the figure below, yellow line is the predicted model; purple line is the predicted perfect model. The mean absolute error (MAE) of predicted model and the original Thursday’s data is 2.12. This means that the accuracy of this model is worse than the original model. Moreover, the generalizability of this model is not good as well. Therefore, comparing with every week’s model, thursday’s model is not generalizable enough to predict the other day of the week.

To analyze the influence of the variable of time of day. We hold out the mid-day data in time of day variable. Then we use evening data and morning data to predict mid-day’s vacant spots. We can see midday’s predicted model performs better than evening’s and morning’s, whose mean absolute error is 1.87. Overall, the generalizability of all these three model is not good.

5 Discussion

The model is not effective enough since our MAE is around 1.82 for our in-sample model. We still need to improve our model. When there are enough samples within the neighborhoods (in our model, most data are in the downtown area), the model will perform better than those that lack samples (those in peripheral areas). Moreover, the model is not generalizable enough. This means that the performance of model varies across different neighborhoods. Therefore, as long as we have enough data within the study neighborhood, our model can perform quite well.

Peak Hour perform quite well as a temporal variable in our model, even rather than time variable itself. This means that peak hour does matter and will cause different results of vacant spots. This finding can also explain our assumption at the beginning of this report. Since most peak hours will highly be associated with traffic congestion, and vacant spots will also be affected by traffic congestion.

Distance to schools and distance to garages have a good performance in our model as spatial variables. While the distance to CBD does not has an obvious performance. The possible reason might be that most of the data are already within the CBD. Therefore, they have the same relations with this variable.

We use the 25%-sample models to test the effectiveness and generalizability of the model. MAE in the test set is 2.12, which has a worse result than the in-sample model. The variation of the numbers of vacant spots will reach to 2 spots. The accuracy result is moderate. However, the model is hard to apply to the other district except using in the downtown area. That is, the model predicts quite well within CBD, but relatively worse in Capitol Hill and University District (which are both outside the CBD boundary.) The probable reason may also relate to lack of sample data outside downtown.

In the spatial-lag model and temporal-lag model, both show that the model is not generalizable enough. This result will also relate to the uneven allocation of time data. In general, our model seems not to be that effective and needs to be improved.

6 Conclusion

We will still confidently recommend our model to the public, even though the effectiveness of the model still needs to be improved. Our model still can help the public to find a vacant spot in a timely manner or help people to decide whether they should drive their car in that period (especially peak hours in downtown). We can also offer some most important variables to help people to make their final decisions. For example, if the parking spots are close to a school, people should avoid these streets; if it is peak hour, people should better not try to park their car in the downtown.

To improve our model, we will recommend people to include business permission into the model. Because the scale of neighborhood variable is still too big to predict the model. Business permission can separate business areas (such as commercial, residential, or mixed-use) on a smaller scale. To access better generalizability, we suggest to highly include more data outside the downtown area.
